> 1. **"The Gruffalo" by Julia Donaldson and Axel Scheffler**: This is a children's book about a mouse's walk in the woods where he uses clever tricks to avoid being eaten by various predators ("bad guys"). In the process, he also invents an imaginary Gruffalo creature, which unexpectedly turns out to be real.
> 
> 2. **"Where the Wild Things Are" by Maurice Sendak**: This book tells the story of Max, a boy who sails to an island inhabited by 'wild things' (potentially 'bad guys'). However, Max tames them with a magical trick and becomes their king.
> 
> 3. **"Llama Llama Red Pajama" by Anna Dewdney**: In this story, Baby Llama views his mother as a 'bad guy' when she leaves him alone in his room at bedtime. It's a relatable and gentle way to introduce feelings of fear and loneliness to young children.
> 
> 4. **"Room on the Broom" by Julia Donaldson and Axel Scheffler**: Featuring various 'bad guys' (a witch, a dragon, and a scary bird), this story covers themes of friendship and problem-solving.
